<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910628-0042</DOCNO><DOCID>910628-0042.</DOCID><HL>   International:   Manila Raises Estimate   Of Damage From Volcano</HL><DATE>06/28/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A10</SO><IN>INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND STATISTICS (IEN)</IN><NS>INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND ANALYSIS (IEN)</NS><RE>FAR EAST (FE)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)PHILIPPINES (RP)</RE><LP>   MANILA, the Philippines -- Damage from the eruption ofMount Pinatubo is widespread and could exceed that caused bythe devastating earthquake that rocked the Philippines lastyear, the government said.   Finance Secretary Jesus Estanislao said rehabilitation andreconstruction costs for agriculture and infrastructuredamage already reported were estimated at 3.5 billion pesosto five billion pesos ($128.2 million to $183.1 million).</LP><TEXT>   But he added that the figure could eventually surpass the15 billion to 16 billion pesos of damage caused by thepowerful earthquake that struck the main island of Luzon inJuly 1990.   Mr. Estanislao said the estimates, the first comprehensivefigures released by the government, don't include the costsof providing food and medicine to the estimated 200,000people who have fled to temporary relocation centers. Theestimates are much higher than those offered by governmentand private economists soon after Mount Pinatubo beganerupting earlier this month.</TEXT></DOC>